# Agent Preferences (Draft)

This file captures observed conventions from a sampled theme codebase. It is **drafted from sampling** (not every file). Please correct anything that is off.

## General
- Indentation: 2 spaces.
- Keep existing style in the file you are editing (don’t reformat unrelated lines).
- Prefer blank lines between logical blocks.
- For `schema` arrays in sections/blocks, put each object on its own lines, never `},{`. Preferred:
  ```
  {
  },
  {
  }
  ```
 - When asked to create a new **section**, follow the “Section Creation” workflow below.

## Section Creation
- Inputs: a `filename` and a human-readable `section name`.
- Create `sections/<filename>.liquid` by copying `sections/custom-section-template--with-theme-blocks.bak`.
- In that file, replace:
  - `mfr-core__custom-section` with the provided `filename`.
  - `Custom Section` with the provided `section name`.
- Create `styles/sections/<filename>.scss` with:
  - Imports:
    - `@import "../variables";`
    - `@import "../tools/util/util";`
    - `@import "../tools/mixins";`
    - `@import "../site-specifics";`
  - Sub-filename rule: use the portion after `__` (e.g., `mfr-core__accordion-section` → `accordion-section`).
  - Structure:
    ```
    .<filename> {
      .<sub-filename> {
      }
    }
    ```
  - Indentation: 2 spaces.

## Naming Conventions (Sections)
- Core sections: `mfr-core__<section-name>` (core, reusable; frequently added).
- Project-specific sections: `mfr-<project-initials>__<section-name>` (e.g., Project Name → `mfr-pn__...`).
- Template-specific sections: `mfr-<template>__<section-name>` for templates like product, search, metaobjects, blogs, collection, article, etc.
- Part-specific template sections (exclusive to section groups): header, footer, offcanvas, modals.
  - Section groups currently: `header`, `footer`, `offcanvas`, `modals`.

## Block Creation (Theme Blocks)
- Inputs: `block name` and target section (e.g., `mfr-core__accordion-section`).
- Create a new theme block file under `blocks/` as directed.
- Block naming convention: `_<section-name>__<block-name>` (e.g., `_footer__menu`).
- The block **must include schema** with: `name`, `class`, `settings`, `blocks`, and `presets`.
  - If no initial `settings` are provided, leave `settings: []`.
  - If no initial `blocks` are provided, leave `blocks: []`.
- Class naming: use a handleized version of the block name (e.g., “Image Text” → `image-text`).
- Markup should include an inner element using the `__inner` convention:
  - Outer class: `image-text`
  - Inner class: `image-text__inner`
- Settings are grouped under `header` inputs (e.g., "Max Width Settings"), and all related settings follow until the next `header` input.
- Optional settings group: **Block Layout Controls** (add only when requested).
  - When asked to add it to a block: insert `{%- render "settings__block-layout-controls" -%}` in the block markup and append the schema settings at the bottom of the block settings.
  - Implemented via snippet `snippets/settings__block-layout-controls.liquid`.
  - Settings include:
    - `paragraph` labels for Width, Padding, Margin.
    - First-level checkboxes: enable Width/Padding/Margin.
    - Width controls (mobile/desktop): width + max-width with unit select (px, %, vw, custom) and custom text input for calc values.
    - Padding controls (mobile/desktop): X/Y checkboxes and left/right/top/bottom number inputs (px only).
    - Margin controls (mobile/desktop): X/Y checkboxes and left/right/top/bottom number inputs (px only).

## Liquid / HTML
- For top-level Liquid tags (first-level `if`, `for`, `schema`, etc.), use trim markers `{%- ... -%}` to avoid whitespace when blocks render empty. This enables safe `:empty` styling.
- Liquid tags often use trim markers: `{%- ... -%}` and `{{- ... -}}`.
- HTML attributes frequently broken onto multiple lines when long; keep alignment similar to nearby markup.
- Alpine attributes usually use single quotes for JS payloads: `x-data='{ ... }'`, `x-on:click='...'`.
- For Alpine events, use `@` shorthand (e.g. `@click`).
- Liquid filter chains are often line-broken and aligned under the variable.
- BEM-style class names are common.
- Line length: keep it readable. Break lines when needed.
- For Liquid `{%- render ... -%}` calls, always put each parameter on its own line for readability, e.g.:
  ```
  {%- render "component__lazyload-image",
    image: block.settings.image,
    width: 240,
    alt: alt -%}
  ```

## SCSS
- 2-space indentation; nested selectors are common.
- Uses `@import` (not `@use`).
- Mixins/utilities such as `@include breakpoint(...)` and `rem-calc(...)` are common.
- For pixel values, use `rem-calc(...)` (e.g. `rem-calc(15)` for `15px`).
- No spaces inside `rem-calc(...)` (use `rem-calc(15)`, not `rem-calc( 15 )`).
- Section headers use block comments with divider lines.

## JavaScript
- 2-space indentation, semicolons, trailing commas in objects/arrays.
- Double quotes for strings.
- Alpine components typically follow:
  - `window._mfrAlpineRegistered` guard.
  - `document.addEventListener("alpine:init", () => { Alpine.data("Name", () => ({ ... })) })`.
- Global Alpine stores live in `scripts/theme/*` and use `Alpine.store("name", { ... })`.
- New Alpine components usually live in `scripts/components/` with file and `x-data` name `MFR` + PascalCase (e.g., `MFRDropdownMenu`), and should be created by copying `scripts/components/alpine-script-boilerplate.js` and replacing `MFRComponentName`.
- To load a component in a section/block/snippet, use `{% render 'script__section', file: "MFRComponentName.js" %}` (file name matches the component file).

## Alpine Usage in Liquid
- `x-data` may be empty for simple scopes: `x-data`.
- Inline Alpine objects are used in attributes with single quotes.
- Store access via `$store.<name>` and `Alpine.store("name")` in scripts.